title: Public_Geology/250k_Surface_Geology
description: These data contain statewide 1:250,000-scale geology data for Washington State. Features include: continental ice limits, contacts, faults, folds, and geologic units. This dataset was tailored for use at a scale of 1:250,000; use at larger scales would be inappropriate.

title: Public_Geology/500k_Surface_Geology
description: These data contain statewide 1:500,000-scale geology data for Washington State. Features include: contacts, faults, folds, and geologic units.This dataset was tailored for use at a scale of 1:500,000; use at larger scales would be inappropriate.

title: Public_Geology/Earthquake
description: This service contains six point, line, and polygon feature classes pertaining to seismogenic features in Washington State, including: 1) active faults (faults with demonstrable Quaternary-age activity), 2) active folds (folds with demonstrable Quaternary-age activity), 3) paleo-seismic trench locations (excavations made for use in studying and documenting potentially active faults), 4) PNSN earthquakes (earthquake catalog data obtained from the Pacific Northwest Seismic Network greater than 1 M and <25 km in depth), 5) relocated earthquakes (a subset of the PNSN earthquakes of accurately relocated earthquake hypocenters), and 6) relocation processing areas (areas used to group clusters of earthquakes during hypocenter relocation processes).

title: Public_Geology/Geothermal
description: This data service includes one feature class and five related tables that present information on the location, physical characteristics, temperature, and water chemistry analyses of thermal and mineral springs in Washington State. This dataset includes warm springs, hot springs, mineral springs, and fumaroles in which temperature was recorded. Data were gathered from all available published and unpublished literature, as well as recent data gathered through a U.S. Department of Energy geothermal grant in support of the National Geothermal Data System.

title: Public_Geology/Hydro
description:
In 2018, WGS received grant funding from the USGS to become a data provider for the National Groundwater Monitoring Network (NGWMN). WGS, in partnership with local water agencies, obtains and curates groundwater level and quality data. A data subset of these wells are selected that fit the criteria required for the NGWMN. Through web services, WGS data is obtained by the NGWMN which can then be consumed by the public through the NGWMN map services and data downloads. Currently, WGS is in partnership with Thurston, Kitsap, and Island Counties, and plan to forge additional connections with other water agencies in the State in the years to come.

DNR groundwater monitoring network

The Department of Natural Resources owns many wells throughout the State that are used on State-owned land leases for agriculture and grazing. In partnership with the Product Sales and Leasing Division, WGS has performed water level measurements and data compilation of wells located in the Southeast Region. Many wells have data from the 1970’s to today, and will prove invaluable when determining water availability for current and future leasing. WGS has created a GIS-based database that can be used for Product Sales and Leasing. This aids in management decisions and observing trends in groundwater resource availability.

title: Public_Geology/Oil_and_Gas_Wells
description: These data contain point locations that represent oil and gas test well sites in Washington State from 1890 to present. Oil seeps were first reported in Washington about 1881 along the sea cliffs on the west side of the Olympic Peninsula. Natural gas seeps associated with mud cones and mounds were also reported in this same general area. Of all the exploratory wells that have been drilled in Washington to date, 249 reported shows for oil and gas. In 1965 the Jackson Prairie natural gas storage project was developed, which remains the Northwest's largest natural gas storage facility.

title: Public_Geology/Subsurface_Geology
description:
These data are intended to be used by geologists, engineers, planners, private-sector geoscientists, and the general public to identify geologic hazards, perform analyses of slope stability, downslope and downstream impacts, storm water management, and identify mitigation opportunities for construction or other land-development projects. Subsurface data is also used in mining, oil and gas exploration, carbon sequestration, and geothermal exploration.

It was compiled from a variety of sources including GeoMapNW, Washington State Department of Transportation, Washington State Department of Ecology, various counties, cities, and water resource agencies. It is not intended to be a complete inventory of borings in Washington State and, at present, includes only a small fraction of this total. The Washington Geological Survey is adding more borings to this dataset as time and resources permit.

title: Public_Aquatics/WADNR_PUBLIC_AQR_BATHYINV
description: This is a working inventory of Puget Sound and outer coast bathymetry dataset footprints for Washington State. The data come from many sources, with varying spatial accuracies. These data should be considered preliminary, and not representative of the full extent of all surveys. This inventory is in no way complete, and is intended to be expanded upon and improved. Initial focus of these polygons is within Puget Sound, the Strait of Juan de Fuca, and the Georgia Straits. NOAA has created a similar inventory for the outer coast and off-shore areas to aid in Marine Spatial Planning and data prioritization. Some overlap between this feature layer, and the NOAA inventory may occur.

title: Shared/FuelStations
description: This data set depicts Washington State Department of Transportation (WSDOT) and Washington State Patrol (WSP) fueling stations. Type of fuel available at fueling station is designated as: G=Gas; D=Diesel; B=BioDiesel; P=Propane; E=Electric. WSDOT Region codes are: 1=Northwest,2=North Central,3=Olympic,4=Southwest,5=South Central,6=Eastern.

title: Topo/KingCo_Contours
description:
The elevation isolines in this map were generated from a digital ground model (DGM) that was constructed from lidar data. The full set of isoline source data contains contours at either a 5- or 10-foot interval depending on geographic location and elevation. (For a full explanation, see https://www5.kingcounty.gov/sdc/Metadata.aspx?Layer=contour005.)

This map displays various contour intervals depending on map scale, from a 5- or 10-foot interval at the largest scale, to a 100-foot interval at intermediate scales, to a 500- or 1,000-foot interval at very small scales. Negative-value contours are included.

title: ClimateChange/AveWinterTemp_CMIP3
description:
Historical and projected change in average winter temperature. CMIP3 projections. HUC8 geography.

Watershed averages for historical conditions (1970-1999) and the projected change for ten global models. Two time periods are considered: the 2040s (2030-2059) and the 2080s (2070-2099), based on a moderate greenhouse gas scenario (A1B). Results are only shown for watersheds for which at least 8 out of the 10 models agree on the direction of change.
energy: climate change impact on energy production and consumption

title: ClimateChange/W5_T_winter_B
description:
Average winter temperature (Dec-Feb).

Geographic units: HUC10.

The layers in this map all reference the same dataset which includes historical values plus two projections each for two future time periods, 2050s and 2080s, based on lower and higher greenhouse gas emission scenarios, RCP 4.5 and RCP 8.5.

The five individual map layers each symbolize a different time period and scenario.

title: Imagery/HXIP_2020_IR_NAD83_MOSAIC
description: Digital aerial infra-red imagery for Washington state was collected by Hexagon as part of the 2020 NAIP Imaging Program. Imagery was collected between June 30, 2020 and November 2, 2020 using Leica ADS100 digital camera systems. The project was flown at heights ranging from 16,500 ft msl to 20,500 ft msl resulting in a nominal GSD of 30cm. Four band images were collected to support both 3-band natural color (RGB) and false color infrared (FCIR) orthoimage products. Aerotriangulation and orthorectification were done with the Leica Xpro software package, version 6.4 and ortho mosaics were created with Inpho Orthovista 8.0. 4-band RGBN 8-bit Ortho images were created in a DOQQ tiling scheme.

title: Imagery/HXIP_2019_IR_NAD83_MOSAIC
description:
Digital aerial imagery for Washington state was collected by Hexagon as part of the 2019 NAIP Imaging Program. Imagery was collected between June 30, 2019 and November 2, 2019 using Leica ADS100 digital camera systems. The project was flown at heights ranging from 16,500 ft msl to 20,500 ft msl resulting in a nominal GSD of 30cm. Four band images were collected to support both 3-band natural color (RGB) and false color infrared (FCIR) orthoimage products. Aerotriangulation and orthorectification were done with the Leica Xpro software package, version 6.4 and ortho mosaics were created with Inpho Orthovista 8.0. 4-band RGBN 8-bit Ortho images were created in a DOQQ tiling scheme.

These data are not for public distribution and should only be used by authorized users. This product is protected by a statewide license agreement that needs to be reviewed and signed prior to use. Contact the Washington OCIO Geospatial Program Office to review the license agreement or to become an authorized user.

title: app_services/oog2
tags: West Virginia,West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection,EnergyAtlas,app_services
description:
This service uses data from the RBDMS database, which was adpoted by the WVDEP department of Oil&Gas in August 2016. It is designed as a replacement for the original oog service, which used data from the superceeded ERIS database.

WVDEP will create new versions of its mapping applications to utilize this service, and the oog service will be depriciated and eventually removed.

The primary change with the new service is the data represents actual or proposed well locations, while the older service represented locations associated with permits received and issued by the Office of Oil & Gas. The practical effect is there is no longer multiple records associated with a particular permit id that plot at the same location; there is only one record and one geographical feature.

title: aasg/WVGeologicMap
tags: West Virginia,WV Geological and Economic Survey,EnergyAtlas,aasg
description:
In 1968 the West Virginia Geological and Economic Survey (WVGES) published a State Geologic Map. The topographic base was compiled from Army Map Service 1:250,000 scale map sheets. In 1998 the WV Division of Environmental Protection (WVDEP) scanned the hardcopy geologic maps at 300 dpi, 8-bit color, and then georeferenced them. Rock unit boundaries were digitized off the images and attributed by WVDEP. The USGS-Water Resources Division later revised the attributes of large water bodies and referenced the datum to NAD83. WVGES augmented the map in 2008 to remove the water bodies and used surrounding geology. Metamorphic features were also added in 2008 along with "GeoAge" font notation to render proper geologic labelling for the map.

The attribute table contains information about the age, rock type (lithology), formal names, and coal seams of the rock units. Structure type and names for separate fold and fault coverages also exist with this service.

title: aasg/WVWellheaders
tags: West Virginia,WV Geological and Economic Survey,EnergyAtlas,aasg
description:
A well is a facility defined by its function to extract fluids from within the earth. A well may be a simple hole in the ground (generally not the kind of wells we're interested in here...), but in general will consist of a dug shaft or drilled borehole. Drilled wells may include one or more boreholes (well bores) that are accessed from the surface at an origin collar, which defines the origin of the well. Individual boreholes in the well my have origin points (collars) that are located within existing boreholes in the well (e.g. sidetracks). The most common situation, especially for water wells, is a well consisting of a single borehole with a collar that is coincident with the well origin.

Well header features represent individual wells, and are the anchor for a variety of observations and other features.

From: http://www.stategeothermaldata.org/data_delivery/content_models/well_header

title: Geology/WVAeromagneticData
tags: West Virginia,WV Geological and Economic Survey,EnergyAtlas,Geology
description:
A reference map of the total intensity magnetic field of the earth in gammas published by the West Virginia Geological and Economic Survey in 1978.

In May/June 2007, two hardcopy map sheets of the 1978 Aeromagnetic Map of West Virginia were scanned at 300 dpi 8-bit color by the WV GIS Technical Center (http://http://wvgis.wvu.edu/). The scanned TIFs were converted to index color mode, and resampled to 150 dpi. The map sections were then mosaicked together and georeferenced to a 15-minute Longitude/Latitude grid.

title: Geology/WVGravityData
tags: West Virginia,WV Geological and Economic Survey,EnergyAtlas,Geology
description:
A reference map of Bouguer gravity values with axes of persistent highs and lows published by the West Virginia Geological and Economic Survey in 1987.

In May/June 2007, two hardcopy map sheets of the 1987 Bouguer Gravity Map of West Virginia were scanned at 300 dpi 8-bit color by the WV GIS Technical Center (http://wvgis.wvu.edu/data/dataset.php?ID=272). The scanned TIFs were converted to index color mode, and resampled to 150 dpi. The map sections were then mosaicked together and georeferenced to a 15-minute Longitude/Latitude grid. Data for the gravity stations was taken from Geonet, the United States Gravity Data Repository System.

title: OilGas/MarcellusPlusGeology_062018
tags: West Virginia,WV Geological and Economic Survey,EnergyAtlas,OilGas
description: Net shale thickness (isochore) data for the Marcellus Formation in West Virginia. Data developed during peer-reviewed study addressing the distribution and thickness of formally and informally recognized Middle and Upper Devonian rock strata with focus on the Marcellus and other organic-rich shales. Nearly 400 wells were studied, primarily using gamma-ray geophysical well logs, to develop a statewide formalization of the lithostratigraphic nomenclature. Also includes data for the Onondaga Limestone and equivalents.
energy: Oil and gas in the Marcellus geological formation

title: DW_Map_Dynamic/EN_Image_Basemap_Leaf_On_Index
description:
This service provides an Index to help determine the aerial photography acquisition date for 2020 USDA National Agricultural Imagery Program (NAIP) air photos of Wisconsin that display in the WI DNR Image Service “EN_Image_Basemap_Leaf_On”. The NAIP 2020 aerial photography is natural color, leaf-on, 0.6-meter resolution imagery. The image service has also been supplemented with 2021 NAIP imagery for MN and IA counties that lie along Wisconsin's western boundary.

WI DNR acknowledges the USDA Natural Resources Conservation Service for making source data available. For more information, contact the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources, Bureau of Technology Services - GIS Section through DNR's feedback form: https://dnr.wi.gov/feedback/index.asp?MessageConcerning=GEO

title: DW_Image/EN_Image_Basemap_Leaf_On
description:
The data source for this Image Service is statewide, natural color, leaf-on imagery of Wisconsin with 0.6-meter pixel resolution, from the 2020 USDA National Agricultural Imagery Program (NAIP). Flights occurred in the Summer and Fall of 2020 for the entire State of Wisconsin. The service has also been supplemented with 2021 NAIP data for counties in Minnesota and Iowa along the western Wisconsin border. In areas where the 2020 and 2021 overlap, the 2020 Wisconsin data is on top. Use this services companion index service (https://dnrmaps.wi.gov/arcgis_image/rest/services/DW_Map_Dynamic/EN_Image_Basemap_Leaf_On_Index/MapServer to identify flight dates).

WI DNR recognizes the USDA for making source data available; for more information, see: https://www.fsa.usda.gov/programs-and-services/aerial-photography/imagery-programs/naip-imagery.

This service will be updated as newer NAIP imagery becomes available. For more information about this service, contact the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources, Bureau of Technology Services - GIS Section through DNR's feedback form: https://dnr.wi.gov/feedback/index.asp?MessageConcerning=GEO
